Suitable in size and armament for a stand in for a Tau Emissary class light cruiser for the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic. Bare and armed variants. Not my finest work, I will be the first to admit. This is not an easy hull shape to design in CAD! But it's done, and now you have this vicious little cruiser to play with! 

There is a hole for a base step under the hull, drill through the circle on the underside. My intent is for this to be printed in one go, from stern to prow. The prow will need some support.

I am not affiliated with GW in any way! Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use (though you're welcome to upload them to get them printed that way for yourself).

Suitable in size and armament for a stand in for a Tau Custodian class fleet carrier for the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic. The highlighted circle on the underside image is where there's a void built into the lower hull component for a mounting peg. The hole is 3 mm in diameter. The bare wings take 3x medium railgun turrets and 1x small ion turret apiece.

*** The correct scaling is 0.7x. I've uploaded a correctly scaled file Custodian v21 rescaled.stl***

I am not affiliated with GW in any way! Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use (though you're welcome to upload them to get them printed that way for yourself).

2019-03-24 - Made all the ruts a bit wider to make them catch paint better.
2019-04-22 - As requested added the whole upper part of the hull as one piece. Just requires the bridge and lower hull printing separately. (Custodian v20)

EDIT: increased diametre of the pegs that connect the rings to one another and the cap piece, and the size of the guide pegs from the innersphere connector to the ring 2 cross beams. tl:dr made it better

No idea how this prints in a single piece, or the supports involved, as it's really meant to be printed in pieces.

The rings and cap are meant to be put together with a bit of luck and a keen eye, I provided no guides. ring 1 (big one) on the inside, ring 2 next, then cap. Don't overthink where they attach.

Once those are assembled, the inner ball attaches to the Ring_2 cross-support piece, with guide pegs to line up a better fit found on the end of the innerball connector arms.

Print doubles of the rings and cap, of course.
